an France]]\n|-\n| [[Caroline Quentin]]\n|-\n| [[Joel Dommett]]\n|-\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |4\n| rowspan=4 |Traybakes\n| rowspan=4 |Mini [[Yorkshire pudding|Yorkshire puddings]]\n| rowspan=4 |Future Aspiration \n\nBiscuit Scene\n|[[James Blunt]]\n| rowspan=4 |{{Start date|2020|03|31|df=y}}\n| rowspan=4 | \n|- \n|[[Alison Hammond]]\n|- \n|[[Alex Jones (Welsh presenter)|Alex Jones]]\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n|[[Joe Sugg]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |5\n| rowspan=4 |\n| rowspan=4 |\n| rowspan=4 |\n|[[Kelly Brook]]\n| rowspan=4 |{{Start date|2020|04|07|df=y}}\n| rowspan=4 | \n|- \n|[[Mo Gilligan]]\n|- \n|[[Robert Rinder|Rob Rinder]]\n|-\n|[[Carol Vorderman]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{Official website|URL=http://thegreatbritishbakeoff.co.uk/}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b010n3q1 ''The Great British Wedding Cake'']\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03qgyqf ''The Great Sport Relief Bake Off'']\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b052sj1d ''The Great Comic Relief Bake Off'']\n* {{UKGameshow|The_Great_British_Bake_Off|The Great British Bake Off}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=1877368|title=The Great British Bake Off}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=2255405|title=The Great Sport Relief Bake Off}}\n{{Div col end}}\n\n{{The Great British Bake Off|Suppliers=Academy Marquees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great British Bake Off, The}}\n[[Category:2010 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British reality television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British reality television series]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British cooking television programmes]]\n[[Category:Channel 4 television programmes]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:The Great British Bake Off| ]]\n[[Category:2010s British cooking television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British cooking television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|GBBO|the ornithological organisation|Great Basin Bird Observatory}}\n{{Short description|British television baking competition}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Great British Bake Off\n| image                    = The Great British Bake Off title.jpg\n| alt                      = A dark cake on a white plate, topped with raspberries\n| genre                    = [[Baking]] <br />[[Reality television|Reality]]\n| creator                  = \n| developer                = \n| director                 = Andy Devonshire <small><br/>(2010\u20132012, 2014\u2013)</small><br />Scott Tankard <small>(2012\u20132013)</small>\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = [[Mel Giedroyc]]<br />[[Sue Perkins]]<br />[[Sandi Toksvig]]<br />[[Noel Fielding]]\n| judges                   = [[Mary Berry]]<br />[[Paul Hollywood]]<br /> [[Prue Leith]]\n| theme_music_composer     = Tom Howe\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language                 = [[British English|English]]\n| num_series               = 10\n| num_episodes             = 94 (and 28 specials) <!-- As of 29 October 2019 -->\n| executive_producer       = Anna Beattie <small>(2010\u2013)</small> <br />Richard McKerrow <small>(2010)</small> <br />Sarah Thomson-Woolley <small> (2016\u20132017)</small> <br />Kieran Smith <small>(2012)</small>\n| producer                 = Samantha Beddoes <small>(2013\u20132014)</small><br />Amanda Westwood <small>(2012)</small>\n| location                 = [[Cotswolds]], [[Scone Palace]], [[Sandwich, Kent|Sandwich]], [[Bakewell]], [[Mousehole]], [[Fulham Palace]] <small>(all 2010)</small> <br />[[Valentines Mansion]] <small>(2011)</small> <br />[[Harptree Court]] <small>(2012\u20132013)</small> <br />[[Welford Park]] <small>(2014\u2013)</small>\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 60 minutes\n| channel                  = [[BBC Two]] <small>(2010\u20132013)</small><br />[[BBC One]] <small>(2014\u20132016)</small><br />[[Channel 4]] <small>(2017\u2013)</small>\n| company                  = [[Love Productions]]\n| distributor              = [[BBC Studios]]\n| picture_format           = [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = Stereo\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2010|8|17|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]'' <br />''[[Bake Off: The Professionals]]'' <br />''[[The Great British Bake Off: An Extra Slice]]'' <br />''[[The Great Pottery Throw Down]]'' <br />''[[Junior Bake Off]]''\n| website                  = http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-great-british-bake-off\n| production_website       = https://thegreatbritishbakeoff.co.uk/\n}}\n'''''The Great British Bake Off''''' (often abbreviated to '''''Bake Off''''' or '''''GBBO''''') is a British television [[baking]] competition, produced by [[Love Productions]], in which a group of amateur bakers compete against each other in a series of rounds, attempting to impress a group of judges with their baking skills, with a contestant being eliminated in each round, with the winner being selected from the contestants who reach the finals. The first episode was aired on 17 August 2010, with its first four series broadcast on [[BBC Two]], until its growing popularity led the [[BBC]] to move it to [[BBC One]] for the next three series. After its seventh series, [[Love Productions]] signed a three-year deal with [[Channel 4]] to produce the series for the broadcaster.<ref name=\"Bake Off Move 2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/12/bbc-loses-great-british-bake-off/|title=BBC loses Great British Bake Off, as Channel 4 swoops for corporation's biggest show|last=Foster|first=Patrick|date=12 September 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> However, [[BBC Studios]] still owns the global distribution rights to the show, which are set for renewal in 2028.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/a807901/bbc-worldwide-still-has-the-international-rights-to-great-british-bake-off-so-there/|title=BBC Worldwide still has the global Bake Off rights|last=Nissim|first=Mayer|date=2016-09-14|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nThe programme was originally presented by [[Sue Perkins]] and [[Mel Giedroyc]], with judges [[Mary Berry]] and [[Paul Hollywood]]. Following its move to Channel 4, the current presenters are [[Noel Fielding]] and [[Sandi Toksvig]], with Hollywood and [[Prue Leith]] as the judges.<ref name=\"New Bake Off Host\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/great-british-bake-off-207-hosts-judges-noel-fielding-to-co-host-the-new-channel-4-series-a7633946.html|title=Great British Bake Off 2017: Noel Fielding to co-host the new Channel 4 series|last=Hooton|first=Christopher|date=17 March 2017|website=[[The Independent]] |publisher= |access-date=17 March 2017|quote=}}</ref> In chronological order, the winners are [[Edd Kimber]], [[Joanne Wheatley]], [[John Whaite]], [[Frances Quinn]], [[Nancy Birtwhistle]], [[Nadiya Hussain]], [[Candice Brown]], [[Sophie Faldo]], [[Rahul Mandal]] and [[David Atherton (baker)|David Atherton]].\n\nThe series is credited with reinvigorating interest in baking throughout the United Kingdom and Ireland, with shops in the UK reporting sharp rises in sales of baking ingredients and accessories.<ref name=\"Impact\"/> Many of its participants, including winners, have gone on to start a career based on bakery, while the [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] award-winning programme has spawned a number of specials and [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] shows: a celebrity charity series in aid of [[Sport Relief]]/[[Comic Relief]] or [[Stand Up to Cancer]]; ''[[Junior Bake Off]]'' for young children (broadcast on the [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]] channel, then on the Channel 4 from 2019); after-show series ''[[The Great British Bake Off: An Extra Slice|An Extra Slice]]''; and ''[[Bake Off: The Professionals]]'' for teams of [[pastry chef]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/food-and-drink/news/everything-you-need-to-know-about-bake-off-creme-de-la-creme/ |title=Everything you need to know about Bake Off: Creme de la Creme |author=Saffron Alexander |date= 29 March 2016 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nThe format of the series is used as the basis for two BBC Two series, ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]'' and ''[[The Great Pottery Throw Down]]''. Under the title '''''The Great British Baking Show''''', the series has also been shown in the United States and Canada. It also has appeared in other countries, and the format has been sold to television producers globally, where local versions are made.\n\n==Background==\n===Development===\n[[File:Victoria sponge (14287044448).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Competitive baking, such as making [[Victoria sponge]] (''pictured''), is part of the classic English village [[f\u00eate]] which inspired the series.<ref name=\"Fete\"/>]]\nThe baking competition was conceived by producer Anna Beattie after she spoke to a friend who had seen 'bake-offs' in America.<ref name=\"telegraph 2012\"/> Beattie was also inspired by the classic English village [[f\u00eate]] baking competitions; she said: \"I loved that idea of village fetes and an old-fashioned baking competition with people who only wanted to bake a good cake.\"<ref name=\"Fete\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/jul/20/bake-off-behind-the-scenes|title=Behind the scenes at The Great British Bake Off|first=Louise|last=Carpenter|date=20 July 2013|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> However, Beattie failed to interest any channel in the idea for four years. \n\nIn early 2009, they pitched the idea to [[Janice Hadlow]], then controller of BBC Two.<ref name=\"rayner\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/20/-sp-great-british-bake-of-paul-hollywood-mary-berry-sue-perking-mel-giedroyc-interview-jay-rayner|title=The Great British Bake Off: 'Now we're on BBC1, Mary Berry demands a golden throne'|work=The Guardian|date=20 July 2017|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> The pitch was successful, and Hadlow and Commissioning Editor [[Charlotte Moore (TV executive)|Charlotte Moore]] commissioned the programme,<ref name=\"woman and home\">{{cite web |url=http://www.womanandhome.com/news-and-entertainment/537890/it-took-four-years-of-pitching-to-get-bake-off-commissioned|title=It Took Four Years of Pitching To Get Bake Off Commissioned |first=Victoria|last=Young|date=5 August 2015|work=Woman and Home|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/food/bake-off |title=Nigella cooks up an Italian feast for BBC Two as raft of new food programming is announced|work=BBC|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> which was then developed over the next six months. The development team first selected [[Mary Berry]] as a judge, and following an audition [[Paul Hollywood]] was also appointed. [[Sue Perkins]] and [[Mel Giedroyc]] were approached to be presenters of the show.<ref name=\"rayner\" /> Reproducing the surroundings of the English village f\u00eate, the series is filmed in bunting-draped [[Pole marquee|marquees]] in scenic gardens.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10253084/The-Great-British-Bake-Off-its-like-a-village-fete-in-your-sitting-room.html|title=The Great British Bake Off: it's like a village fete in your sitting room|first=Michael|last=Hogan|date=20 August 2013|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Broadcast and personnel changes===\nOn 17 August 2010, the first episode of ''The Great British Bake Off'' was shown on [[BBC Two]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tv/entries/1bf82f28-d52e-3da6-82df-eb2ae8cb96b0 |title=Mary Berry: Judging The Great British Bake Off|date= 31 August 2010|work=BBC|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> It stayed on BBC Two for four years, grew in popularity and became the most popular programme on that channel. In its fifth series it was moved to [[BBC One]] where it stayed for three years. It was the most-watched programme on British television in 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/media/12054696/Great-British-Bake-Off-dominates-list-of-most-watched-shows-of-2015.html |title=Great British Bake Off dominates list of most-watched shows of 2015|author= Patrick Foster|date=17 December 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/21/great-british-bake-hands-bbc-clean-sweep-top-ten-most-viewed/|title=Great British Bake Off hands BBC clean sweep of top 10 most-viewed shows of 2016 \u2013 but how will the corporation cope next year?|first=Patrick|last= Foster|date=21 December 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> Following extended negotiations, Love Productions announced that the seventh series of the show would be the last broadcast by the BBC. On 12 September 2016, Love agreed to a three-year deal to broadcast the show on [[Channel 4]].<ref name=\"Bake Off Move 2\"/> Giedroyc and Perkins subsequently announced that they would not be returning when the show moves to its new network.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37355065|title=Great British Bake Off: Mel and Sue to quit as hosts|date=13 September 2016|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=13 September 2016}}</ref> On 22 September, Berry announced that she would also be leaving the show when it moved to Channel 4,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37437907|title=Mary Berry to leave Bake Off ahead of Channel 4 move|date=22 September 2016|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=22 September 2016}}</ref> while Hollywood later announced he would stay.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/sep/22/mary-berry-leave-great-british-bake-off-paul-hollywood-bbc-mel-giedroyc-sue-perkins|title=Mary Berry to leave Bake Off \u2013 but Paul Hollywood agrees to stay|first=Jane|last=Martinson|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> In March 2017, it was announced that [[Prue Leith]] would join Hollywood as a judge, while [[Noel Fielding]] and [[Sandi Toksvig]] would take over as presenters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/16/noel-fielding-and-sandi-toksvig-to-host-new-great-british-bake-off |title= Noel Fielding and Sandi Toksvig to host new Great British Bake Off |first=Alice |last=Ross|date=16 March 2017 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>  After 3 years presenting the show, Toksvig announced her departure in 2020,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51133199 |title=The Great British Bake Off: Sandi Toksvig to leave after three years |date=16 January 2020 |work=BBC }}</ref> to be replaced by [[Matt Lucas]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/matt-lucas-great-british-bake-off-noel-fielding-sandi-toksvig-new-series-channel-4-a9393391.html |title=Great British Bake Off: Matt Lucas to replace Sandi Toksvig as host of Channel 4 show|first=Adam |last=White |work=The Independent |date=11 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Format ==\nThe programme operates on a weekly elimination process to find the best all-around baker from the contestants, who are all amateurs.  The applicants to the show are assessed by a researcher, followed by an audition in London with two of their bakes. They then undergo a screen test and an interview with a producer. A second audition involves the applicants baking two recipes for the judges in front of the cameras.<ref name=\"telegraph 2012\" /> Ten contestants were chosen for the first series, twelve for the following two series, thirteen for the fourth and tenth,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heritage |first1=Stuart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/aug/20/meet-the-2019-great-british-bake-off-contestants-from-the-teacher-to-the-terminator |accessdate=13 September 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=20 August 2019}}</ref> and twelve from series five to series nine.\n\nIn each episode, the amateur bakers are given three challenges based on that week's theme: a signature bake, a technical challenge, and a show-stopper.<ref name=\"telegraph 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9411189/Behind-the-scenes-at-the-Great-British-Bake-Off.html |title=Behind the scenes at the Great British Bake-Off |author=Sarah Stephens |date= 14 August 2012 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref> The three challenges take place over two days, and the filming takes up to 16 hours a day. The contestants are assessed by the judges who then choose a \"[[List of The Great British Bake Off Star Bakers|Star Baker]]\" for the week (introduced in series 2), and a contestant is also eliminated although if the contestant numbers in certain years are not even or there is an non-elimination a week before, then two bakers may be eliminated. In the final round, three bakers are left and a winner is chosen from the three.\n\n; Signature Challenge: This challenge is for the amateur bakers to show off their tried-and-tested recipes for bakes they might make for their friends and family.\n; Technical Challenge: This challenge requires enough technical knowledge and experience to produce a certain finished product when given only limited \u2013 or even minimal \u2013 instructions. The bakers are all given the same recipe and are not told beforehand what the challenge will be. The finished products are judged blind and ranked from worst to best.\n; Showstopper Challenge: This challenge is for the bakers to show off their skills and talent. The judges favour a bake that has a professional appearance but is also outstanding in flavours.\n\nIn the first series, the location of the cast and crew moves from town to town each week, but starting from the second series, the competition is held in one location in a specially constructed marquee. Interspersed in the programme are the background of the contestants as well as video vignettes on the history of baking. What each baker intends to bake during a particular challenge is illustrated using animated graphics. These graphics have been created by illustrator Tom Hovey since the show's inception in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsnicethat.com/articles/illustration-tom-hovey |title=Illustration: We interview the artist behind the Great British Bake Off, Tom Hovey|author= Liv Siddall |date=1 November 2013 |work=It's Nice That }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomhovey.co.uk/the-great-british-bake-off/ |title=Tom Hovey }}</ref>\n\n== Series overview ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Series\n! scope=\"col\" | Episodes\n! scope=\"col\" | Premiere\n! scope=\"col\" | Finale\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:gold;\"|Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:silver;\"|Runners-up\n! scope=\"col\"  |Average UK viewers<br />(millions)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10379873/The-Great-British-Bake-Off-moves-to-BBC1.html |title=The Great British Bake Off moves to BBC1 |author=Rachel Moss|date= 15 October 2013|work=Daily Telegraph }}</ref><ref name=\"broadcast\">{{cite news |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/ratings/bbc1-rises-to-the-challenge/5082034.article |title=BBC1 rises to the challenge|date=22 January 2015 |author= Stephen Price |work=Broadcast }}</ref>\n! scope=